          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">EU rethinks Israel</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>Summary: The EU and the traditional Israeli allies are looking to pressure Israel into lifting its blockade of Gaza.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Most EU foreign ministers support reviewing the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-may-25-spotlights-h2-3-eu-israel-association-agreement" target="_blank">EU‚ÄìIsrael Association Agreement</a>. They <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-may-25-spotlights-h2-4-aim-to-pressure" target="_blank">aim to pressure</a> Israel to lift its humanitarian blockade of Gaza. Since 2000, the EU‚ÄìIsrael Association Agreement has regulated political dialogue and economic cooperation between the two sides.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         If a violation of <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-05-2025-article-2" target="_blank">Article 2</a> is found, the EU might consider actual suspension. Although traditionally an ally of Israel, the Netherlands is leading the initiative, with support from 17 member states, including France, Spain, and Ireland. However, European Commission President Ursula von der Leyen and countries like Germany, Hungary, and the Czech Republic oppose these measures. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Meanwhile, Sweden proposed sanctions against Israeli ministers over Gaza policies, but Hungary blocked efforts to sanction West Bank settlers. Separately, the UK, France, and Canada warned Israel of "concrete actions" if the situation in Gaza does not improve.</p>
