      <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
        China and the US compete for LATAM
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>Summary: Most Latin American countries prefer a non-aligned approach to choosing between China and the US. </strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        China is <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-may-25-analysis-h1-5-increasing-its-influence" target="_blank">increasing its influence</a> in Latin America through trade, funding, and the Belt and Road Initiative (BRI). They are the largest trading partner of Latin America. China positions itself as a reliable partner, offering funds without political conditions and rejecting the ‚Äúvalue-based system‚Äù often attached to US foreign policy. China has taken a different approach. This difference boosts the appeal of strategic non-alignment.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        This provoked a strong reaction from the Trump administration, which used tariffs, sanctions, and threats to counter China. Threats over Panama‚Äôs canal operations and trade penalties on Mexico and Colombia exemplified this. The US wants them to pick a side. However, this style can further alienate allies. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          However, Brazil illustrates a third path. While it is a founding BRICS member and trades heavily with China, President Lula turned down BRI membership in 2024, showing a wish for independence. Brazil prefers balanced relations and development led by its people, similar to India‚Äôs non-aligned approach. Colombia and Mexico are also skeptical about choosing between the US and China. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        This flexibility helps them gain benefits from both while keeping their sovereignty. However, the pressure from the US and China‚Äôs strong position could show that more challenging choices may come later. If the US continues aggressive tactics without better options, non-alignment will probably stay the primary strategy for Latin America's largest economies.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
