</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/rimland-heartland-nicholas-spykman-eurasian-geopolitics.png" alt="The Rimland and Heartland regions, as defined by geopolitical theorist Nicholas Spykman in the Rimland Theory, highlight strategic zones of Eurasian influence" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>The Rimland and Heartland regions, as defined by geopolitical theorist Nicholas Spykman in the Rimland Theory, highlight strategic zones of Eurasian influence.</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        A Dutch American professor at Yale University, Nicholas Spykman, coined the ‚Äú<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-may-25-foundation-h1-11-rimland-theory" target="_blank">Rimland Theory</a>‚Äù early in the 20th century. The theory strongly stresses the strategic value of coastal areas around Eurasia. Spykman debates whether controlling rimland regions like Western Europe, the Middle East, South Asia, Southeast Asia, and East Asia is essential for global power.
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      This theory counters Halford Mackinder‚Äôs <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-may-25-foundation-h1-12-heartland-theory" target="_blank">Heartland Theory</a>, which focuses on Central Asia and other landlocked areas as geopolitical chokeholds. Spykman considered the rimland more critical due to its population, economic activity, and gateway to land and sea routes. According to this theory, controlling the rimland means controlling Eurasia, which in turn means controlling the world. </p>
       <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
     This theory greatly influenced US foreign policy during the Cold War, especially the containment strategy to limit Soviet influence in these key areas. The theory highlights the need to keep a balance of power in coastal zones to prevent any single nation from dominating Eurasia. </p>
     <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
     Some critics of the theory say it did not consider many factors. For example, they did not consider modern missiles and warheads. He also didn‚Äôt consider regional conflicts, like those in India and Pakistan. The study also shows bias against Asian countries. This theory and the Heartland are still relevant to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-may-25-foundation-h1-13-global-strategic-discussions" target="_blank">global strategic discussions</a>, especially in areas like the South China Sea, Eastern Europe, and the Middle East, where territory control is essential.  </p>
       </mj-text>
